Your implementation has a potential issue with how you're handling empty search queries. Let's review the current flow:

## Current Implementation Issue

In your `onQueryTextChange` handler, when the text is empty, you're calling `observeViewModel()` which reattaches all observers to your `viewModel`. This is inefficient because:

1. You're creating new observers every time the query becomes empty
2. The previous observers aren't removed, potentially causing duplicate observers
3. This can lead to multiple UI updates for the same data changes

## Suggested Improvement

Instead of fully re-observing everything when the query is empty, you should just update the displayed data. Here's how to improve it:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/githubrepofinder/ui/MainActivity.kt
// ... existing code ...
 override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
 // ... other code remains the same ...

 // Observe data changes (call this only once)
 observeViewModel()

 binding.searchView.setOnQueryTextListener(object : SearchView.OnQueryTextListener {
 override fun onQueryTextSubmit(query: String?): Boolean {
 query?.let {
 if (it.isNotEmpty()) {
 viewModel.searchRepositories(it)
 }
 }
 return true
 }

 override fun onQueryTextChange(newText: String?): Boolean {
 newText?.let {
 if (it.isNotEmpty()) {
 // Only switch to local search when query isn't empty
 loadLocalSearchResults(it)
 } else {
 // Load the main repository list when query is empty
 // but don't re-observe
 viewModel.loadDefaultRepositories()
 }
 }
 return true
 }
 })

 // ... existing code ...
 }

 // New method to handle local search without re-observing
 private fun loadLocalSearchResults(query: String) {
 viewModel.searchLocalRepositories(query).observe(this) { repos ->
 adapter.submitList(repos)
 binding.emptyView.visibility = if (repos.isEmpty()) View.VISIBLE else View.GONE
 }
 }
// ... existing code ...
```

You'll need to add a new method in your `RepositoryViewModel`:

```kotlin
fun loadDefaultRepositories() {
 // This should just reload whatever default repositories you want to show
 // Maybe re-fetch the last successful query or load from cache
 // Or simply call searchRepositories("language:kotlin") again
 searchRepositories("language:kotlin") 
}
```

This way:
1. You only set up your observers once in `onCreate`
2. When search text changes, you just change which data is being displayed
3. When search is empty, you return to your default repository list

This approach is more efficient and avoids potential memory leaks or duplicate observers."},{"role":"user","content":"<user_query>
